<LEADPARA>  THERE are birds and butterflies on the bag, and the brand name includes the
word "Nature" in leaf-green print. What does this picture of perfect packaging
tell you about the fertilizer inside?;    Not a thing.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MEANING OF 'GREEN' CAN BE TRICKY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     All it tells you is that the company that manufactured the plant food knows
its marketing, because green -- as in environmentally conscious -- is the
color in garden products these days. In the fertilizer business, as with other
garden supplies, green is the color of money, too, and fertilizer is the
fastest-growing segment of the marketplace.;    Unfortunately for consumers,
discerning if there is anything truly "green" inside those fertilizer bags is
even harder than selecting the product with the right N-P-K ratio ever was.;
 In the N-P-K ratio, it's necessary to know that nitrogen (N) governs foliage
growth, phosphorus (P) helps the flowers bloom, and potassium (K) is
responsible for root development. But savvy shoppers also need to know
precisely what "natural," "organic" and other current fertilizer jargon means.
The words may sound familiar, but watch out.;    As in the early days of
"lite," "natural" and "organic" foods, a kind of free-for-all is taking place
in the garden marketplace.;    Not only are new fertilizer formulas being
introduced to meet the demand for "green" plant foods, but some companies are
simply relabeling their old products to imply an environmental sensitivity and
cash in on the enthusiasm.;    Because it can take several years or longer for
government labeling regulations to catch up with trends in new products,
claims stated on the bag may not be what they seem. A fertilizer labeled
"organic," for instance, is not necessarily non-chemical. It can -- and often
does -- contain synthetic ingredients under current state label laws, most
frequently in the form of urea. By law, a "natural" product cannot contain
chemicals, but it can contain both organic and inorganic materials.;    First,
consumers must decide which side of the chemical debate they are on.
Proponents of non-chemical fertilizers, for instance, say there are several
reasons to buy them, besides the current snob appeal of things green.;
Chemical fertilizers frequently are manufactured from precious reserves of
fossil fuels, antagonists say, and their manufacture also is fuel-intensive,
burning petrochemicals and producing pollution.;    "All-natural organic"
fertilizers -- those that contain only materials derived from plant or animal
products, which tend to be the most expensive, are the choice in strict
organic-gardening circles.;    They make use of renewable resources, waste
products or byproducts, such as manures, meals and composts from other
industries that might otherwise wind up in dumps.;    A caveat: While it is
essential environmentally that we learn to recycle all our waste products
efficiently, some of them may contain substances that could pose potential
threats, especially if used to fertilize the food garden:;    (check) Leather
meal often is high in chromium, an element used in the tanning process.;
(check) Cottonseed meal can be packed with pesticides, because cotton farming
is pesticide-intensive.;    (check) Mushroom compost (the medium mushrooms are
grown in commercially) is likewise exposed to lots of chemicals.;    (check)
Sewage sludge, or tankage, may be high in heavy metals. These need to be
cleaned and tested for safety first, but at present this is not always done,
or even required under current law.;    "If they're following the law, legally
we have to register the product," said Stephen Markarian, acting supervising
inspector with the New York State Division of Plant Industry, Department of
Agriculture and Markets, which registers companies to distribute fertilizers.
"But we're beginning to look at more of these questions. There's a lot of work
ahead to do.";    Slow action;    All-natural organic fertilizers generally
are slower-acting than chemical ones, requiring a couple of weeks or more to
produce results.;    Because they are taken up gradually, they will not burn
plants. Slow-release chemical fertilizers also are formulated to be less apt
to burn than quick-release chemical nitrogen sources.;    But perhaps the most
important distinction is that all-natural organic fertilizers put organic
matter into the soil, proponents stress, not just give a quick shot in the arm
to plants.;    "The plants may not know the difference, but the soil does,"
said Bill Wolf, vice president of the Organic Foods Production Association of
North America, a non-profit educational trade group, and founder of Necessary
Trading Co., a longtime leading supplier of products for organic gardening and
farming. "I just listen to the earthworms. Long term, a 100 percent natural
organic (fertilizer) builds healthy soil while producing healthy plants and
healthy people.";    Read the labels;    What's a consumer to do? Read, read,
read -- as in labels. Some tips on what to look for:;    (check) "Try not to
be led by the company name," said Paul McNelly, a fertilizer regulatory
adviser with the American Association of Plant Control Officials, a group of
individual state officials that publishes rules many states adopt or use as
guidelines in devising their own laws.;    "A brand name can twist the words
'natural' and 'organic' as much as they like. It's 'creative' marketing, so to
speak," he says. Likewise, friendly nature scenes on the package do not
necessarily a natural product make.;    (check) Select a product that promises
slow release. Those rich in organic materials will naturally be slow; when
buying chemical fertilizers, spend the extra amount for non-burning,
slow-release formulations.;    (check) If you want to go strictly organic,
look for the words "all-natural organic" or "100 percent natural organic."
Scan the ingredient list for familiar-sounding substances that come from plant
or animal sources (hoof meal, bone meal, feather meal, fish emulsion, manures,
seaweed and so forth).;    (check) Check the N-P-K ratio numbers for another
clue to whether a product is truly all-natural and organic. It is unlikely
that anything with numbers adding up to more than 15 is 100 percent organic,
unless significant amounts of blood meal (an organic substance very high in
nitrogen) were added. Otherwise, suspect that the product has been "boosted"
with some amount of chemicals.;    (check) Do not waste organic resources.
Compost kitchen and yard wastes, then add to soil. Leave clippings on the
lawn, where they can return nitrogen to the soil naturally. Don't rely solely
on bagged fertilizers -- chemical or non-chemical.  </TEXT>
