<HEAD>Initial Effort to Tighten Auto Emissions Standards Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House members who want stricter auto emissions
standards say they won't let an initial defeat prevent another bid
to toughen President Bush's clean air bill.
   Administration opponents on the Energy and Commerce environment
subcommittee failed Tuesday to amend the bill, as they sought to
make auto requirements far tougher than those in smog-choked
California.
   Panel Chairman Henry A. Waxman's plan lost on a voice vote, but
the California Democrat said his forces would make another attempt
_ possibly today, when the subcommittee considers more amendments
to the administration plan.
   ``Many didn't want to go with our provisions,'' he said, but
predicted some members might support ``a middle-ground, something
like the California standards.''
   California has the toughest auto pollution requirements in the
country, exceeding federal requirements for the rest of the nation,
because its ozone problem is so serious.
   Motor vehicle emissions are a prime source of ozone, although
some pollutants also contribute to the other problems the bill is
trying to address: acid rain and airborne toxic chemicals.
   Ozone is a highly reactive gas that is the prime ingredient of
smog, a term coined by combining smoke and fog. Ozone is produced
by the combination of hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides in the
presence of sunlight and heat. Both gases are produced from mobile
sources _ cars, trucks and buses _ but also from stationary sources
_ major industrial plants, such as utilities, and some small
businesses.
   The outgunned Waxman, who is closely allied with environmental
organizations, conceded defeat without requesting a roll call.
   ``Sometimes you don't want them on record so they can rethink
their position and come around,'' said Waxman, who can renew his
proposal in the full Energy and Commerce Committee and the House
floor if he loses in subcommittee. The Senate has not begun
amending clean air legislation.
   Rep. Norman F. Lent, R-N.Y., the main GOP sponsor of the Bush
legislation, said Waxman's proposals would have cost consumers an
extra $500 per car if fully implemented by model year 2000. For
that expense, he said pollution under Waxman's plan would only be
cut an additional 2.7 percent compared to the Bush proposal.
   Motor vehicles are mainly responsible for ozone pollution,
although some emissions also release toxic chemicals and a
component of acid rain.
   Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., said he supported Waxman's plan in
order to ``send ... the right kind of signal'' to the auto industry
and the public: that Congress backs ``the strictest limits.''
   But he added, ``We don't know where those numbers are going to
lead us.''
   The latter point was made repeatedly by Lent, who said the
technology doesn't exist to meet the Waxman standards, but only is
alive in ``the dreams of the authors'' of the amendment. ``Even
California is smart enough not to adopt these standards,'' he
argued.
   Waxman's plan would have limited hydrocarbon emissions to 0.25
grams per mile from 1993 through 1999, and 0.125 grams per mile
after that.
   Nitrogen oxides, an ingredient of acid rain, would have been
capped at 0.4 grams per mile from 1993-99, and 0.2 grams afterward.
   Carbon monoxide, a toxic pollutant, was set at 3.4 grams per
mile from 1992-99 _ retaining current law _ and 1.7 grams afterward
under the Waxman proposal.
   The Bush standard for hydrocarbons is 0.25 grams per mile by
1998; for nitrogen oxides, 0.7 grams by the same year; and
retention of the current 3.4 gram carbon monoxide limit.
   California's limits for hydrocarbons starting in 1995 will be
0.25 grams per mile for 50,000 miles and 0.31 grams between 50,000
and 100,000 miles.
   The state's nitrogen oxide limit, already in effect, is 0.4
grams up to 50,000 miles. The carbon monoxide standard now is 3.4
grams but rises to 4.2 between 50,000 and 100,000 miles.
   Current federal law outside California requires car limits of
0.41 grams per mile for hydrocarbons, 1 gram for nitrogen oxides
and 3.4 grams for carbon monoxide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

