Plant Will Be Closed</HL>
<DD> 01/15/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CHV
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM) </IN>
<DATELINE> SAN FRANCISCO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Chemical Co. said it will close and mothball its ammonia-fertilizer plant in Pascagoula, Miss., by Jan. 28 because of a continuing slump in the nitrogen-fertilizer industry.

   The plant, which has annual output of about 525,000 tons, is one of four nitrogenfertilizer facilities that Chevron Chemical currently owns and operates.

   The Chevron Corp. unit will reassign the plant's 40 employees to other jobs at its Pascagoula oil refinery, where the ammonia plant is located.
The unit added that it intends to reopen the plant "when market conditions justify" operating the facility.

   The nitrogen-fertilizer industry in the Midwest and Gulf Coast states has been hit hard by a recent increase in fertilizer imports, a spokesman for the unit said.
Chevron Chemical expects demand for nitrogen fertilizers to remain low through 1987.

   Last month, the unit sold two Midwest specialty fertilizer facilities and purchased two nitrogen-fertilizer plants in the Pacific Northwest as part of an effort to concentrate fertilizer operations in that region.

   Chevron Corp. has petroleum and related operations.

</TEXT>
