<HEAD>President's Supporters Win One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of President Bush's clean air bill
defeated an attempt Tuesday to make it require auto exhausts
cleaner than those now in force in smog-plagued California.
   The tough provision proposed by Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif.,
was defeated by voice vote in the House Energy and Commerce
environment subcommittee he chairs.
   The subcommittee is considering amendments to Bush's legislation
to clean the skies of ozone, acid rain and airborne toxic chemicals.
   The outnumbered Waxman, who is closely allied with environmental
organizations, accepted defeat without a roll call, saying he
wanted to avoid forcing members to take a public position against
stringent automobile controls.
   Waxman, promising to return with a compromise that still would
toughen Bush's auto requirments, said, ``Sometimes you don't want
them on record so they can re-think their position and come
around.''
   Rep. Norman F. Lent, R-N.Y., ranking Republican on the parent
committee and the main GOP sponsor of the Bush legislation, said
Waxman's proposals would have cost consumers an extra $500 per car
if fully implemented for model year 2000. For that expense, he said
pollution under Waxman's plan would only be cut an additional 2.7
percent compared with the Bush legislation.
   Estimates of the cost of current auto emissions contols have
clustered around $1,500 per car in recent years.
   Lent said the technology doesn't exist to meet the Waxman
standards, which he said represented ``the dreams of the authors
and have no basis in technological fact.''
   Whatever happens in the subcommittee, the battle over auto
standards is expected to surface again in the full Energy and
Commerce Committee and the House floor. The Senate has not yet
begun work on clean air legislation.
   Motor vehicles are a major contributor to ozone pollution, in
some areas the principal contributor, through the emission of
unburned fuel vapors. They also emit oxides of nitrogen and carbon
monoxide
   Ozone, the prime ingredient of smog, is produced by the reaction
of hydrocarbons _ unburned fuel _ and nitrogen oxides in the
presence of sunlight and heat. Because of its ozone problems,
California has tougher auto pollution standards than the rest of
the nation.
   Waxman's plan would have limited hydrocarbon emissions to 0.25
grams per mile _ the standard for California starting in 1995 _
from 1993 through 1999, and 0.125 grams per mile after that.
Outside California, cars are limited to 0.41 grams per mile under
current law.
   Nitrogen oxides, which also contribute to acid rain, would have
been capped at 0.4 grams per mile from 1993 through 1999, down from
1 gram now, and 0.2 grams after 1999.
   Waxman's proposed limit for carbon monoxide was 3.4 grams per
mile from 1992 through 1999, the current standard, and 1.7 grams
afterwards.
   The administration's proposed standard for hydrocarbons is 0.25
grams per mile by 1998; for nitrogen oxides, 0.7 grams by the same
year; and for carbon monoxide, retention of the current 3.4 gram
limit.
   Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., who supported Waxman, said, ``We are
really in the dark. Our eyes glaze over at these numbers.''
