<LEADPARA>  A study by the National Academy of Sciences has found that smog is so poorly
understood that much of the nation's effort to control it may be misdirected.;
  The study, scheduled for release Wednesday, says progress in meeting
standards for smog "has been extremely slow at best" and blamed problems in
measuring smog and accounting for variations in weather.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STUDY HINTS SMOG EFFORTS ARE IN VAIN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Smog forms when two classes of chemicals react together in sunlight:
volatile organic compounds that occur in gasoline and various industrial
processes, and nitrogen oxides, which are created when nitrogen and oxygen in
the atmosphere combine in the intense heat of an engine or boiler.;   Air
pollution control officials have concentrated on organic compounds; the study
suggests they should have directed more effort toward nitrogen oxides.;   The
study raises the possibility that billions of dollars invested to reduce
organic emissions have been misdirected because efforts to reduce nitrogen
oxides have been neglected.;   Michael Bradley, executive director of an
organization of eight Northeastern states that take joint action on air
pollution issues, said: "Directionally, it's probably all true. It's just a
matter of how alarmingly you want to put it.";   But another expert, Terry
Yosie of the American Petroleum Institute, said that in light of the report
the pollution control measures in place or proposed "may also be significantly
flawed."  </TEXT>
