<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Approach to Fighting Smog Is Faulted
   In a New Report by Sciences Academy
   ----
   By Rose Gutfeld
   Staff Reporter of the Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/16/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<NS>
ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)
</NS>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A new study by the National Academy of
Sciences is likely to become a key weapon in the oil and auto
industries' battle against tighter pollution controls on cars
and fuel.
   According to the report, the government's 20-year effort
to reduce ground-level ozone -- the prime ingredient in smog
-- may have been misdirected. "There's been a lack of
progress in many areas of the country that's both
disappointing and perplexing," said John Seinfeld, chairman
of a committee of scientists that prepared the report.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a result of scientific and technical deficiencies, the
study said, policy makers have seriously underestimated the
amount of volatile organic compounds in the atmosphere and
given insufficient attention to controlling nitrogen oxide.
Ozone is formed when volatile organic compounds and nitrogen
oxide react together in sunlight.
   Volatile organic compounds are produced mainly from motor
vehicles, evaporating solvents, the chemical and oil
industries and vegetation. Nitrogen oxide comes from the
combustion of fossil fuel by motor vehicles and electric
power plants.
   The report, scheduled for release this week, was made
available over the weekend after copies were leaked to the
press. The American Petroleum Institute and the Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers Association provided some funding for the
study, which was primarily financed by the Environmental
Protection Agency and the Energy Department.
   The report was required under last year's revisions to the
federal clean air act, which hit hard at the oil and auto
industries. By suggesting that the nation's approach in
attacking smog is flawed, the study could bolster industry
efforts to fend off even tougher requirements.
   Some states are considering whether to join California in
requiring far tougher controls on emissions on cars and fuel
than are required nationally.
   "Why are states going for the most expensive option that
will produce the least gain in air quality?" asked Terry
Yosie, a vice president at the API. "We need a national
debate on the effectiveness of our ozone control policy."
   Environmental groups disagreed vehemently, however. David
Hawkins, senior attorney at the Natural Resources Defense
Council, contended that the report shows the need for a
redoubled attack against volatile organic compounds as well
as increased attention to nitrogen oxide.
   Among the report's major findings are the following:
   -- Volatile organic compounds emitted by trees and other
vegetation play a bigger role in smog formation in some areas
than officials have recognized. In cities such as Atlanta,
more volatile organic compounds are emitted by natural
vegetation than by human sources.
   -- The undercounting of volatile organic compounds has led
to a miscalculation of the ratio of hydrocarbons to nitrogen
oxides. This ratio is important in determining which
pollutant is more important to attack in reducing smog. As a
result, in some areas, officials have focused insufficiently
on nitrogen oxide.
   -- The government's main method for measuring smog is
faulty, partly because it doesn't adequately take into
account fluctuating weather patterns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

