   Diesel Designers Try
   To Lighten Dark Clouds


</LP>
<TEXT>
   NEW technologies to cut diesel engines' emissions are
emerging in response to tougher air pollution rules. Detroit
Diesel has developed diesel engines that run on methanol and
emit fewer pollutants. The engine recently met this year's
tough California standards for diesel bus emissions, says a
spokeswoman for the company.
   Diesel designers aren't giving up on traditional fuel.
They are developing precision turbochargers and
fuel-injection systems to burn diesel fuel more cleanly. If
the systems work well enough, then catalytic converters can
be used to cut emissions further (the converters, now used
with gasoline engines, would otherwise be overwhelmed by
diesel soot). Donaldson Inc., Minneapolis, is working on
another idea: a "trap" that uses an electrical heater to
oxidize and break down particulate matter.
   But these technologies don't do much to cut another class
of diesel pollutants, nitrogen oxides, which contribute to
smog and acid rain. A potential solution from Sandia National
Laboratory uses a chemical that, when fed into an exhaust
system, reacts with nitrogen oxides and produces harmless
nitrogen and water.
   Another technology is in the works at PlasMachines, a
Natick, Mass., start-up. It uses an electronic device to
break down nitrogen oxides, dispensing with the need for
chemical additives, says Stanley Rich, president. He figures
that if mass-produced, the device would cost a few hundred
dollars, less than existing pollution-control systems for
cars.
   New diesel cars aren't currently sold in California
because their emissions of soot and nitrogen oxides exceed
the state's maximums. Several Northeastern states are
expected to adopt similar regulations soon, further crimping
sales of diesel cars. The federal and state rules also pose
problems for makers of diesel engines for buses, trucks and
industrial machines. Though reducing pollution, the rules
also cut use of fuel-efficient diesel vehicles.


   Environmental Start-Ups
   Gain New Green Sources


   THE environmental industry is getting a boost from new
capital conduits.
   Venture Capital Network, a Cambridge, Mass., nonprofit
group that matches investors with entrepreneurs, recently
created an environmental category in its computer database.
The new category was inspired both by investors' growing
interest in environmental start-ups and by the proliferation
of such companies, says Roger B. Wilson, the network's
executive director. For a $250 fee, investors participating
in the network can get a set of three-page business proposals
by environmental entrepreneurs, and from those in other
business areas if desired, each of whom also pays $250 to
participate.
   Another channel has been created by Ally Capital, a
Sausalito, Calif., company that lends money for
corporate-equipment leases. It recently announced plans to
raise $100 million from institutional investors to finance
such leases by environmental start-ups. Allen Gold, president
and chief executive officer, says Ally plans to finance the
leasing of everything from earthmovers to instruments for
toxic-waste testing. In recent months, Ally has made
financing commitments of $20 million to various environmental
companies, he adds.


   And Little Children Shall
   Find Uses for Discards


   RECYCLING markets may be down, but finding customers is
child's play for recycler Leonard Gottlieb.
   For 20 years Mr. Gottlieb has run a thriving business that
recycles industrial discards, mainly by selling them to
children. Housed at Boston's Children's Museum, his Recycle
shop blends well with the place's hands-on exhibits, such as
a "climbing wall" for the upwardly mobile set.
   The shop sells things by the bag-patrons can load up a
grocery-sized one for $5. Mr. Gottlieb says he "smokes out"
the stuff from Boston-area companies, which otherwise would
throw away the defective, outdated or otherwise unsellable
items. They include plastic planters, foam rubber pieces,
computer keyboard buttons, wood rectangles and a barrel full
of plastic E.T. figurines-leftovers of a faded fad. With a
little glue, the items can be turned into spaceships, funny
hats, sculptures, or mock clubs to beat the rival siblings.
   "They're a staple for any situation with kids," says Leigh
Faramarzpour, who teaches art to children and is loading up
20 bags of summer stock at the shop.
   The operation started making money for the museum within a
few years of its inception, Mr. Gottlieb says, and has been
copied in the U.S. and Europe. Though it doesn't cut the
trash stream much, it helps show that recycling can work --
to kids and parents, and also to the shop's corporate
contributors, he notes.


   Odds and Ends


   AMERICANS rank corporate environmental crimes as more
serious than insider trading, antitrust violations and worker
health and safety violations, according to a nationwide
survey by management consultant Arthur D. Little Inc. Some
74% of 1,000 people surveyed said executives should be held
personally liable for their companies' environmental
offenses. . . . Another recent survey, commissioned by
environmental consultant Pilko &amp; Associates, found that 89%
of 200 senior U.S. executives feel their companies are doing
a good or excellent job of managing environmental problems.
But 43% acknowledged that their companies had paid fines for
environmental crimes, and 40% said their companies had
recently rejected proposed acquisitions because of concerns
about environmental liabilities.
